content:
Here is a Julia solution using abstract type and concrete type approach:

```julia
abstract type AbstractVehicle end

struct Car <: AbstractVehicle end 
struct Motorcycle <: AbstractVehicle end
struct Bus <: AbstractVehicle end
struct Truck <: AbstractVehicle end

function ispersonal(::Type{Car})
    return true
end

function ispersonal(::Type{Motorcycle})
    return true
end

function ispersonal(::Type{Bus})
    return false
end

function ispersonal(::Type{Truck})
    return false
end

ispersonal(::AbstractVehicle) = false
```

The `ispersonal` function returns true for Car and Motorcycle, and false for Bus and Truck. The last line is a fallback that will return false for any other subtype of AbstractVehicle. Here are some examples:
```julia
@assert ispersonal(Car) == true
@assert ispersonal(Motorcycle) == true
@assert ispersonal(Bus) == false
@assert ispersonal(Truck) == false
@assert ispersonal(struct MyVehicle <: AbstractVehicle end) == false # Test with a new subtype
```
Remember to use `@assert` for testing, as it will throw an error if the test fails.
